# The Lexi Phase
The Lexi Phase is the **first phase** a computer goes through in the Javascript **interpretive language**. The Lexi Phase identifies variables and hoists them to the **top of the scope**.

**Example 1**
*Written code*
var song = "All the stars";
console.log(song);

*Interpreted*
var song;
song = "All the stars";
console.log(song);

*Console*
"All the stars"

Functions are **declarations**, so they are hoisted to the top of the scope along with the variables

**Example 2**
*Written code*
var bar = typeof foo;

function foo(a) {
		return a;
}

*Interpreted*
function foo(a) {     
		return a;
}
var bar;
bar = typeof foo;

*Console*
"function"
# Function Declaration vs. Expression
A function expression **gives a value**, while a function declaration declares the function, but doesn't give a value. You can usually tell if something is **not a expression** if it **doesn't use var**.

**Example**
*Expression*
var foo = function(a) {
	return a;
}

*Declaration*
function log(message) {
	console.log(message);
}
